# Precision Calculator Architecture Plan

## Product Scope

Build the product named in the GitHub issues as a single-screen scientific precision calculator with persistent history, memory registers, keyboard support, and deployment-ready frontend tooling.

## Project Shape

- Framework: React + TypeScript with Vite.
- Styling: Tailwind CSS, with a small global stylesheet for app-level resets and reusable CSS variables if needed.
- Tooling: ESLint, Prettier, TypeScript strict mode, Vitest, React Testing Library, and Playwright for end-to-end coverage.
- Runtime: static frontend app unless a later deployment issue requires a minimal server.

## Proposed File Organization

- `src/main.tsx`: React entry point.
- `src/App.tsx`: top-level app composition.
- `src/styles/index.css`: Tailwind directives and base styling.
- `src/types/calculator.ts`: shared domain types for angle mode, display state, history entries, memory state, parser tokens, and evaluation results.
- `src/lib/storage.ts`: local storage helpers with typed read/write, migrations, and safe fallbacks.
- `src/lib/decimal/`: precision-safe decimal arithmetic adapter and formatting helpers.
- `src/lib/calculation/`: tokenizer, parser, evaluator, scientific functions, operator metadata, and error types.
- `src/state/`: React hooks or reducers for calculator input, history, memory, modes, and persistence wiring.
- `src/components/display/`: primary display and history trail.
- `src/components/buttons/`: core arithmetic grid, scientific function cluster, memory controls, and mode toggles.
- `src/components/layout/`: app shell and responsive calculator frame.
- `src/input/keyboard.ts`: keyboard mapping and normalization.
- `src/test/`: shared test fixtures and render helpers.
- `e2e/`: Playwright workflow tests.

## Shared Types

- `AngleMode`: `"deg" | "rad"`.
- `NotationMode`: `"standard" | "scientific"` or equivalent display preference.
- `CalculatorError`: parse, math-domain, divide-by-zero, overflow, and invalid-input categories.
- `CalculationResult`: decimal value, formatted display, optional error, and source expression.
- `HistoryEntry`: id, expression, result, timestamp, angle mode, and notation mode.
- `MemoryState`: decimal value plus derived `hasValue` flag.
- `ButtonDefinition`: id, label, aria label, role, keyboard aliases, and command payload.

## Issue Dependencies

- Issue #1 enables all implementation and test work.
- Issue #2 establishes the shell used by UI issues #9-#18.
- Issue #3 should land before persistence issues #11 and state-heavy components.
- Issues #4-#8 define the calculation engine and should precede most UI wiring.
- Issues #9-#15 can be built once the shell, shared types, and command model exist.
- Issue #16 depends on stable calculator commands from the button work.
- Issues #17-#18 polish layout after core controls and display are functional.
- Issues #19-#20 depend on the engine, memory, history, and persistence modules.
- Issue #21 depends on the complete user workflow.
- Issue #22 should review the finished engine and UI error states.
- Issue #23 should happen last after build, tests, and runtime behavior are stable.

## Key Design Decisions

- Keep the calculation engine framework-independent so it can be unit tested without React.
- Represent user actions as typed commands shared by buttons and keyboard input.
- Use a decimal library or decimal adapter boundary for all arithmetic so native floating-point behavior is isolated.
- Store history and memory as serializable strings rather than JavaScript numbers to preserve precision.
- Treat display formatting separately from evaluation so scientific notation and degree/radian mode remain explicit.
- Prefer reducer-based state for calculator behavior because input, memory, history, modes, and errors are tightly related.
- Persist only durable user state: history, memory, mode settings, and display preferences.
- Keep the first implementation static and client-only; add server logic only if deployment requirements later demand it.
